{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585293"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14952"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14952"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.04,0.42,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7640"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14952"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"7674"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of a painful, swollen right knee following a fall while playing netball. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right knee is warm, swollen, and tender with reduced range of movement. X-ray shows no fracture. Arthrocentesis reveals blood-stained synovial fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe acute inflammatory response is beginning to occur at the site of injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular storage and release of P-selectin during acute inflammation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Released from both endothelial cells and platelets","Released exclusively from neutrophil granules","Released only from endothelial Weibel-Palade bodies","Released only from platelet alpha granules","Released exclusively from mast cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute inflammation, \u003Cstrong\u003EP-selectin is released from both endothelial cells and platelets\u003C/strong\u003E. It is stored in Weibel-Palade bodies of endothelial cells and alpha granules of platelets, allowing rapid mobilisation to the cell surface in response to inflammatory mediators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils do not store or release P-selectin, making \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleased exclusively from neutrophil granules\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect. The options stating \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleased only from endothelial Weibel-Palade bodies\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleased only from platelet alpha granules\u003C/strong\u003E are both incomplete as they ignore the dual cellular sources of P-selectin. Mast cells do not store or release P-selectin, so \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleased exclusively from mast cells\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EP-selectin is rapidly mobilised to the cell surface within minutes of stimulation by inflammatory mediators. This allows for the initial capture and rolling of leucocytes along the vessel wall, which is essential for the subsequent steps of firm adhesion and transmigration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["P-selectin is stored in both Weibel-Palade bodies of endothelial cells and alpha granules of platelets.","P-selectin mediates the initial rolling adhesion of all leucocytes on activated endothelium.","P-selectin is rapidly mobilised to the cell surface in response to inflammatory mediators."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Punchard NA, Whelan CJ, Adcock I. The Journal of Inflammation. J Inflamm (Lond). 2004 Sep 27;1(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1476-9255-1-1. PMID: 15813979; PMCID: PMC1074343","Geng JG, Chen M, Chou KC. P-selectin cell adhesion molecule in inflammation, thrombosis, cancer growth and metastasis. Curr Med Chem. 2004 Aug;11(16):2153-60. doi: 10.2174/0929867043364720. PMID: 15279555.","Zanoli L, Briet M, Empana JP, Cunha PG, M\u00e4ki-Pet\u00e4j\u00e4 KM, Protogerou AD, Tedgui A, Touyz RM, Schiffrin EL, Spronck B, Bouchard P, Vlachopoulos C, Bruno RM, Boutouyrie P; Association for Research into Arterial Structure, Physiology (ARTERY) Society, the European Society of Hypertension (ESH) Working Group on Vascular Structure and Function, and the European Network for Noninvasive Investigation of Large Arteries. Vascular consequences of inflammation: a position statement from the ESH Working Group on Vascular Structure and Function and the ARTERY Society. J Hypertens. 2020 Sep;38(9):1682-1698. doi: 10.1097/HJH.0000000000002508. PMID: 32649623; PMCID: PMC7610698"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14952"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:44:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:44:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7640"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}